Implement the setcookie( ) function with various arguments using the PHP program.

SOLUTION:
a PHP program that demonstrates how the setcookie() function works with its various arguments.
The function syntax is:
setcookie(name, value, expire, path, domain, secure, httponly);

CODE:
<?php
// 1. Basic cookie (name and value only)
setcookie("cookie1", "SimpleCookie");

// 2. Cookie with expiry time (valid for 1 hour)
setcookie("cookie2", "ExpiresIn1Hour", time() + 3600);

// 3. Cookie with path restriction (available only within /admin folder)
setcookie("cookie3", "PathRestricted", time() + 3600, "/admin");

// 4. Cookie with domain restriction (works only for example.com)
setcookie("cookie4", "DomainRestricted", time() + 3600, "/", "example.com");

// 5. Secure cookie (sent only over HTTPS)
setcookie("cookie5", "SecureCookie", time() + 3600, "/", "", true);

// 6. HttpOnly cookie (not accessible via JavaScript, for security)
setcookie("cookie6", "HttpOnlyCookie", time() + 3600, "/", "", false, true);

// Display cookie values (on page reload)
echo "<h2>Cookie Values:</h2>";
foreach ($_COOKIE as $key => $value) {
    echo "$key : $value <br>";
}
?>

EXPLANATION:
name → "cookie1" → Identifier of the cookie.
value → "SimpleCookie" → Data stored in cookie.
expire → time() + 3600 → Cookie lasts 1 hour.
path → "/admin" → Cookie available only inside /admin folder.
domain → "example.com" → Cookie only valid for that domain.
secure → true → Sent only over HTTPS.
httponly → true → Prevents JavaScript access (protection against XSS).
